Stage Stores (SSI) Michael L. Glazer on Q1 2015 Results - Earnings Call Transcript | Seeking AlphaSign in / Join NowGO»Stage Stores (SSI) Michael L. Glazer on Q1 2015 Results - Earnings Call TranscriptMay.19.15 | About: Stage Stores, (SSI) Stage Stores, Inc. (NYSE:SSI)
Q1 2015 Earnings Call
May 19, 2015 8:30 am ET
Executives
Randi Sonenshein - Senior Vice President, Finance and Strategy, Stage Stores, Inc.
Michael L. Glazer - President, Chief Executive Officer & Director
Oded Shein - CFO, Secretary, Treasurer & Executive VP
Steven Paul Lawrence - Chief Merchandising Officer
Analysts
Heather N. Balsky - Bank of America Merrill Lynch
Pamela Quintiliano - SunTrust Robinson Humphrey
Bob S. Drbul - Nomura Securities International, Inc.
Charles P. Grom - Sterne Agee CRT
David M. Mann - Johnson Rice & Co. LLC
Jeff Van Sinderen - B. Riley & Co. LLC
David J. Glick - The Buckingham Research Group, Inc.
Jeff S. Stein - Northcoast Research Partners LLC
Operator
Good morning and welcome to Stage Stores Conference Call. At this time, all participants are in a listen-only mode. Later, the company will conduct a question-and-answer session and instructions will follow at that time. As a reminder, this conference call is being recorded.
I would now like to introduce your moderator for today's conference call, Ms. Randi Sonenshein, Senior Vice President of Finance and Strategy. Ms. Sonenshein, please begin your conference call.
Randi Sonenshein - Senior Vice President, Finance and Strategy, Stage Stores, Inc.
Thank you, operator. Good morning, and welcome to Stage Stores first quarter conference call. Also with us on the call this morning is Michael Glazer, President and Chief Executive Officer; Oded Shein, Chief Financial Officer; and Steve Lawrence, Chief Merchandising Officer. Michael and Oded will begin with prepared remarks and we will all then be available to take your questions.
Our discussion this morning will include forward-looking statements reflecting our projections for future events and performance. Various factors may cause our actual results to differ materially from those projected in the forward-looking statements. For more information on those factors, please refer to the Risk Factors discussed in our most recent Form 10-K, our other filings with the SEC, and this morning's earnings release. Forward-looking statements speak only as of today's date, and we undertake no obligation to update those statements.
I'll now turn the call over to Michael.
Michael L. Glazer - President, Chief Executive Officer & Director
Thanks, Randi, and good morning, everyone. Thank you for joining us today for our first quarter conference call. I'll begin today's call by providing an overview of our performance for the quarter, and we'll then discuss the progress that we are making on our goals for 2015 and the long-term. Oded will follow with a review of our financial results, and Steve is here as well to answer questions.
We are pleased with our overall performance in the first quarter. While it was challenging from a top-line perspective, our merchandise margin expansion and solid expense management helped to deliver favorable bottom-line results which improved 29% to a loss of $0.27. We achieved this during a difficult selling environment which included a shift in our own marketing calendar that I will describe shortly.
As you have probably already heard from many retailers, there were several factors that put pressure on sales during the first quarter. I have to start with weather because it had a major impact on us as it disrupted sales especially in the South Central and Southeast parts of the country. Some of our stores were closed for extended periods as various government officials deemed road conditions unsafe. Kentucky, where we have 34 stores, was a good example of this and turned out to be our worst performing state for the quarter.
We have 26 stores on the Mexican border. And as most of you know, these are some of our highest volume stores. Sales in those stores suffered as a result of the strong dollar. The weaker peso has made discretionary spending in the U.S. much more expensive for our loyal Mexican national customers. Delays created by the West Coast port strike also had some effect on our first quarter business specifically in footwear.

Then, of course, there is the question of energy and whether the loss of jobs is impacting us or whether lower gas prices are offsetting any drop in employment. It continues to be difficult to measure or pinpoint the answer to that question. If you exclude our border stores, our Texas sales were better than our overall company average. Stores in many cities whose economies are driven by oil drilling such as Odessa and Midland were weaker. But the strongest area in the company in the first quarter was Houston. So, I guess the answer is that it's impossible to make a conclusive call at this time. My opinion for what it's worth is that it is somewhat of a headwind in specific energy areas but not nearly as severe as has been suggested.
With regard to the change in the timing of our advertising for Mother's Day, we saw an opportunity to increase Mother's Day sales and intentionally made a shift in our marketing calendar from the end of the first quarter to the start of the second quarter. This marketing shift created huge excitement at our stores and clearly paid off because it generated record sales for the Mother's Day week.
As I mentioned in our press release, our year-to-date comp sales were positive for the first 14 weeks of the year. Going back to first quarter, cosmetics and home were the best categories while men's and accessories were the weakest. Some of our strongest sales were reflected in the high-profile brands such as Nike, Calvin Klein, Skechers, Estée Lauder and Carter's. Activewear remains the most dominant trend, up double-digits while denim continues to be a little sluggish.
As you know, a primary focus for us is to raise sales productivity. We planned to take a greater share of our customers' wallet and to accelerate growth in our direct-to-consumer business. This will put Stage Stores on a path to consistent sales and earnings growth. To accomplish this, we are focused on four key areas. One, creating a great omni-channel experience; two, increasing our emphasis on trends and styles; three, improving the store environment; and four, better connecting with our customers. First and foremost is our direct-to-consumer business which grew 31% during the quarter. We reached a number of milestones, and for the first time, we had more mobile and tablet visitors than those using a desktop. We launched a mobile optimized site. We expanded the assortments and grew centralized fulfillment, all resulting in a better customer experience.
I am also thrilled to announce that we strengthened our management team with the recent hiring of a new Senior Vice President of e-commerce, Mike Smith. Mike's background includes Signet Jewelers, Home Depot, Spiegel and The Limited. As we previously discussed, our mission is to provide a merchandise assortment that is compelling to our customer with high-profile national brands and updated styles at a great value.
In cosmetics, our plan this year is to roll out Estée Lauder and Clinique counters in 30 stores and Smashbox and Origin counters in 20 more stores. We also plan to continue our home department expansion with 45 more stores this year. In addition to making sure our merchandise selections are compelling, we are focused on improving our store environment. Our customer comes first, and she wants an exceptional shopping experience every day. As part of this key strategy, we shifted capital from opening new stores to updating our existing fleet, with upgrades to fixtures, more mannequins, comfortable fitting rooms, improved lighting, enhanced navigation, and wider aisles.
Our systematic remodeling program has already begun, and we plan to have a small group of stores completed by the end of the second quarter. As you know, our plan is to update over 100 of our stores this year. We should get a slight lift in the third quarter with the bulk of the impact being felt in the critical fourth quarter.

Last but certainly not least, we are taking steps to strengthen our connection to our customer. We are focused on shifting mediums to reach her where she is, that means more digital and mobile, while tailoring our communications to make a more personalized connection. We will also be piloting enhancements to our loyalty program in select markets later this year. In addition, we will continue to leverage and build upon our private label credit card, with a card reissuance in time for the holidays.
In conclusion, the first quarter on its own was challenging from a top-line perspective, but our margin expansion and solid expense management helped to deliver favorable bottom-line results. We are thrilled with our Mother's Day performance and definitely are on track with our expectations. We are reaffirming our annual outlook of flat to positive 2% comparable sales growth and EPS of $1.20 to $1.28. We are confident in our ability to deliver sales and earnings growth this year. Our entire company is focused on and excited about the strategies that we have in place. There are a lot of positives in our plan for the year, and we feel good about the direction of the company and the initiatives that are under way.
I'll now turn the call over to Oded.
Oded Shein - CFO, Secretary, Treasurer & Executive VP
Thanks, Michael, and good morning, everyone. Net sales for the first quarter were $369 million. Comparable sales for the quarter decreased 1.1%. Michael identified the sales driver for the quarter. But let me reiterate that the primary reason for our comp sales decline was our decision to shift our marketing calendar from Q1 to Q2, resulting in shifted sales and lower advertising expenses for the quarter. During the quarter, we saw a 6% increase in AUR offset by a lower UPT and number of transactions.
The gross profit rate increased 100 basis points compared to last year's rate from continuing operations. The merchandize margin component increased 180 basis points, benefiting from the increase in AUR. The gross profit increase was partially offset by higher cost for buying, occupancy and e-commerce reflecting our strategic investment in omni-channel, technology and stores. Expense for the quarter decreased $2.4 million and leveraged 40 basis points to last year due to higher benefit from our private label credit card program, lower advertising cost that shifted to the second quarter, and lower store opening expense.
With regard to our private label credit card, we continue to see strong growth during the quarter with penetration rate increasing 350 basis points over last year's rate. The net loss for the quarter was $0.27 per share, $0.11 per share or 29% better than last year's loss from continuing operations of $0.38 per share. Our share count for the quarter was 31.75 million and the tax rate was 38.9%.
Moving to the balance sheet, we ended the quarter with total merchandise inventories up 8% over last year. More than half of the increase was driven by supply-chain related in-transit inventory as we shipped second quarter merchandise earlier this year. We also had more cosmetic inventory, as this year we operated 63 more stores with Clinique and Estée Lauder counters. On a comp basis excluding cosmetics, inventory was up 0.7%. Borrowings under our credit facility at the end of the quarter were $86.6 million, essentially flat with last year.
Capital expenditure for the quarter, net of landlord construction allowances, totaled $12.2 million. We opened two new stores, completed one remodel and five expansions and installed cosmetic counters in one store. We also closed three stores during the quarter. As Michael noted, we are maintaining our guidance ranges for the year with comp sales between flat and up 2% and EPS between $1.20 and a $1.28.

That concludes my remarks. We would now be happy to take your questions.
Question-and-Answer Session
Operator
Your first question is from Heather Balsky of Bank of America. Your line is open.
Heather N. Balsky - Bank of America Merrill Lynch
Hi. Good morning. Thank you for taking my call. I guess my first question, you just broke out the details around inventory, but I was hoping you might be able to share what inventory looks like post-Mother's Day. And then, as a second question, can you just give us confidence – give color around your confidence about driving comp improvement for the remainder of the year? What kind of do you view as the key drivers, especially in 4Q? Thanks.
Steven Paul Lawrence - Chief Merchandising Officer
Hi. This is Steve. I'll take a shot at answering both questions. From an inventory perspective, as Oded broke it down for you, we gave you comp store inventory of up 0.7%. So, we're trying to be transparent and let you know that's the inventory that's most comparable on a year-over-year basis. Beneath the surface, what I would tell you is that inventory is in very good shape. It's more forward-facing than a year ago. And quite honestly, it's probably in the best place it's been in the three years that I've been here. The delta between the 0.7% and the up 8% is, as Oded mentioned, a chunk of that's obviously cosmetics inventory as we continue to open more stores, which feeds the inventory base.
And then, there's a lot of in-transit in that. A lot of you guys know that port issues became an issue for us and for a lot of people in the back half of last year, in late third quarter, fourth quarter, and even bleeding into this year a little bit. So, we started looking at a key second quarter timing of Father's Day, back-to-school. We did open up some shipping windows with a couple of vendors and those goods did come in from an in-transit perspective. But when you look at the delta between the up 0.7% and the 8%, it's comprised primarily of cosmetics and in-transit, which really doesn't have any sort of a markdown or margin liability associated with it.
In terms of what gives us confidence, going forward, to drive comp, Michael alluded to a lot of the initiatives that we put in place. Really they haven't even started to take hold in the first quarter. We've got a lot of our store updates still ahead of us. As a matter of fact, most of them for the year are still happening, and we'll feel a lot of impact to that in third quarter, but primarily in fourth quarter. We continue to refine and update the assortment, and we're getting some really good wins there as we ramp up our penetration in updated and contemporary in Missi. So, we feel like a lot of the things that we put in place as part of the long range plan are still ahead of us this year and into the next couple of years.
Heather N. Balsky - Bank of America Merrill Lynch
Great. Thank you. And just one last follow-up, with regards to the headwinds you're seeing in your border stores, the reaction to the stronger dollar, have you seen trends worsen from the fourth quarter? How is that based into your guidance? Thanks.
Michael L. Glazer - President, Chief Executive Officer & Director
Heather, it's Michael. I think it has actually gotten a little worse. So, I think as the dollar continues to get strong or frankly maybe said another way that weak peso as it continues to weaken, it has hurt us. There's no question about it. I mean, as you know, those stores are normally the ones that are always outperforming. And now they're actually a drag on our comp store sales at this point. And I don't know there's frankly a whole lot we can do down there at this point from that standpoint.
Heather N. Balsky - Bank of America Merrill Lynch
Thanks again.

