So, I think Michael alluded to the fact, if you ask any member of the management team, we probably all think that there's probably somewhat of a headwind there. It doesn't seem as great as it's been suggested. We feel like there's been other factors that impeded our progress in first quarter, some of which we created for ourselves like the marketing shifts, some of which were out of our control like weather. But I think we've got the appropriate caution built into our plan going forward based off of what we're seeing in the business right now.
Michael L. Glazer - President, Chief Executive Officer & Director
The other comment, Heather, that I would make – or Pam, that I would make, actually, is on those border stores is, even though those are some of our large volume stores or have been certainly in the past, again, it's only 26 out of over 800 stores. So, I wouldn't make more out of it than it is, but it's certainly from a dollar standpoint, or the strong dollar, it's certainly an issue.
To Steve's point about the energy thing, we've been looking at this. Obviously, a lot of people keep calling out the energy thing and how is it impacting us. And I think it bears repeating that despite what some other retailers I know have said, Houston continues to be one of our strong markets. So, I don't know if it's just our particular customer who isn't impacted by the energy in this particular market or what, but it continues. And granted we have a couple of our flagship stores here because it's our home, but it's been very strong here in Houston. You certainly wouldn't know about the energy issue here.
Pamela Quintiliano - SunTrust Robinson Humphrey
