Actually, Jeff, again, we've been saying this actually for a couple quarters now. It's pretty consistent. There's no specific – if you look around the country, as you know, we're in 40 different states, and it's remarkable how consistent it is. Again, within Texas, there were certain issues, as we talked about, the Odessa/Midland or the border, but then Houston offset it. But literally, in terms of the rest of the country, the small stores versus large stores, the JCPenney's markets, whatever other markets, our performance is pretty consistent, and you're talking about just a couple basis points one way or another, nothing significant.
Jeff Van Sinderen - B. Riley & Co. LLC
Okay. And then can you also just touch on your comps in cosmetics and then is that something that you see continuing to be a driver as you continue to roll out counters the rest of the year? And then maybe also if you can just touch on the spring marketing, some of the changes you made this year in terms of personalization, any metrics you can share there to gauge success so far. Thanks.
Michael L. Glazer - President, Chief Executive Officer & Director
Yes. I'll let Steve handle some of the personalization and some of those items. In terms of the cosmetics, listen, you know we've had a terrific track record these last few years, these last few quarters with cosmetics as we continue to roll out the Estée Lauder and Clinique counters. I see no reason for that to change.
As we said earlier, we're going to do about 30 more counters or 30 more stores, actually, with Estée Lauder and Clinique, going to do an additional 20 stores with Smashbox and Origins. I mean that tends to be a real winner for us and there's certainly no sign of that changing. So, I feel really good about that. We're testing in some of our smaller stores. I know the question often comes up how many stores can you continue to roll Estée Lauder and Clinique out to? And every time we give you a number, we seem to be able to exceed it the next couple, the next year or whatever.

Right now we're testing some smaller counters, frankly, that work well, hopefully, in some of our smaller stores which enable us to continue on that path. But we'll see. But so far so good, and feel great about where we are with cosmetics.
Steven Paul Lawrence - Chief Merchandising Officer
In terms of personalization, obviously, a hot topic out there in retail right now. We definitely are looking at ways to continue to reach out to our customer, speak to them on a more one-on-one basis. Some examples of that, for Mother's Day, we actually did a couple different versions. One version went out to only our plus-size customers versus another version went out to more traditional, missy (0:38:25) customers.
We try to personalize emails and texts based off shopping patterns that are out there. We're doing some personalization in terms of direct mail where we're changing it up based off of whether you're a men-centric customer, a home customer, kids customer, et cetera. So, definitely something we're focused on and working on. We're in the early innings on that. It's not like we've got a huge run rate on this so far. But so far really pleased with the results and something we're going to continue to do more and more of.
Jeff Van Sinderen - B. Riley & Co. LLC
