Your next question is from David Glick with Buckingham Research. Your line is open.
David J. Glick - The Buckingham Research Group, Inc.
Thank you. Just a couple quick questions. Your new SVP of e-commerce, you listed a number of companies with relevant experience. Just curious where he came from most recently.
And then secondly, it sounds like men's and accessories, a little tougher. Those are typically – have been strong businesses for you, if I'm not mistaken. Curious what the strategies are to turn that around.
And then third, just some commentary on footwear, which we've been hearing from other companies has been improving and the potential for a strong footwear and resurgent denim business, what that might mean for back-to-school? Thanks.
Michael L. Glazer - President, Chief Executive Officer & Director
Hi, David. Michael. First of all, let me just start with Mike Smith for a second. Most recently he was at Signet, which is I know you're familiar with. The beauty of him coming from Signet, frankly, is that he's used to dealing with multiple nameplates.
So, as you know, Signet I guess has Jared and Kay and Zales and various nameplates, so he's dealt with that issue that obviously we have at times struggled with. And so, that's just one positive why we're happy to have him with us and we think he'll make a big impact here.
Oded Shein - CFO, Secretary, Treasurer & Executive VP
In terms of the businesses you asked about, specifically the men's business, probably our biggest drag there quite honestly has just been our inability at least in the first quarter to sell seasonal products. With some of the weather we experienced, seasonals really were late in opening up. The good news is once we did get into that Mother's Day shift, we did see not only within the women's business the seasonals across all the categories open up.
And speaking a little bit to the marketing shift that we did for Mother's Day, one of the things that we have noticed is that the timing on these events, at least from a brick-and-mortar perspective, seems to be compressing. We used to look at Mother's Day, Father's Day, Easter as two-week events. It seems like more and more, at least from a brick-and-mortar perspective, they're compressing down into a 7-day to 10-day event, which is one of the reasons why we purposely made the shift we did for Mother's Day to move marketing out from two weeks out into the week out and that paid off for us. So, we think that that obviously would work as well for Father's Day.

In terms of accessories, most of the categories within accessories have been pretty solid. Handbag business good; costume jewelry business good. We did have a little softness in fine jewelry. We did see it come back a little bit for Mother's Day. We're very bullish about our handbag business going forward in the second quarter. We're also excited to see some of our seasonal categories there open up like sun. So we think that's already on the road to recovery.
You mentioned shoes. Shoes has been one of our strongest businesses. It was our strongest business last year in the total company, and it was one of our weaker businesses in first quarter. So, when we talk about port issues, I've characterized it as more of an annoyance than a hardcore problem. A few of the shoe buyer, the shoe DMM, they're going to tell you it's more of a problem and that was the area that was probably most impacted by the port strike and slowdowns in deliveries because so much of that does come from China and it comes through the West Coast. We're back in good inventory position in shoes. Shoes, like a lot of the businesses, had a really, really good Mother's Day. We saw the seasonal businesses open up there like sandals and we feel really good about our Father's Day, and really our back-to-school business in shoes. So, we feel like shoes is going to be a tailwind for us the rest of the year.
David J. Glick - The Buckingham Research Group, Inc.
Great. Thanks very much. Good luck.
Oded Shein - CFO, Secretary, Treasurer & Executive VP
Thanks, Dave.
