So, we were north of 40% in penetration. We're consistently seeing quarters over 40%. Again, very excited about that because it's so important with our communication with the customer, increasing loyalty, of course, helping sales and the bottom line. I don't want to get into too much of the income, but certainly the income or the benefits from the credit card program increased nicely in the first quarter.
Jeff S. Stein - Northcoast Research Partners LLC
Okay. And when you relaunched your credit card in the fourth quarter, are there going to be any enhancements to the loyalty program or special incentives to come out and use the new card immediately? I think you did that in 2012.
Michael L. Glazer - President, Chief Executive Officer & Director
Jeff, for sure. I mean, that's something we're going to take advantage of the opportunity of the reissue, obviously, to more than just send out a card, but obviously do some things from a value proposition standpoint that we think will be meaningful and significant, and hopefully certainly not only drive the use of the card but hopefully help our top line as well.

Oded Shein - CFO, Secretary, Treasurer & Executive VP
And, Jeff, as you know, we are constantly thinking and improving our loyalty programs. And over the course of the year, we plan to test a number of different loyalty permutations and see what works best for our customers. So, you've got to think about relaunching the card and also expanding the loyalty program.
Jeff S. Stein - Northcoast Research Partners LLC
How many cards do you plan on sending out and how would that compare to 2012?
Oded Shein - CFO, Secretary, Treasurer & Executive VP
It's over 2 million cards. Our program is constantly growing. I don't know the exact growth rate. We can get back to you with that.
Jeff S. Stein - Northcoast Research Partners LLC
Okay. And just trying to isolate the weather impact. Can you parse out how your comps trended in February compared to March, April on a combined basis?
Steven Paul Lawrence - Chief Merchandising Officer
So, this is Steve. I'll take a shot at that. We had a lot of momentum coming out of fourth quarter, and we saw that continue into the first part of February. I will tell you that in the back half of February in our geography, a lot of ice storms, closures of stores, and it's like hit the brakes and gave back a lot of what we gained, obviously, in the first half of the month. Once we got past February, I would say it was less about ice and snow. It was more about not warm temperatures, but really rain in our geography. I joke with Michael every day, it's raining down here. I think I'm building an ark in my backyard. So, that's impacted our ability to sell seasonals primarily. But certainly, the biggest impact from a store closure and from a ice and temperature was felt in February.
Jeff S. Stein - Northcoast Research Partners LLC
So, Steve, would it be fair, I mean, was February down mid-single digit or not that much?
Michael L. Glazer - President, Chief Executive Officer & Director
Jeff, we're not going to give specific months other than to say the month of February was down for us, and obviously impacted by the weather, as Steve pointed out. The other thing to say on the weather thing is even where we didn't have the stores shut down and all the issues with the roads and so forth, when you get into Easter there, as you know, it really comes down to not – people always keep talking about the timing of Easter and is it too early or is it too late, but it really comes down to what those weather conditions are and whether you're going to start selling some of the seasonal spring-type goods. And obviously, this year that was also kind of difficult.
Jeff S. Stein - Northcoast Research Partners LLC
Okay. And just final question. With respect to store closings, is the number still 10 to 20 for the year?
Oded Shein - CFO, Secretary, Treasurer & Executive VP
That is correct.
Jeff S. Stein - Northcoast Research Partners LLC
Okay, great. Okay, guys. Thanks a lot.
Michael L. Glazer - President, Chief Executive Officer & Director
Thanks, Jeff.
Operator
Ladies and gentlemen, this concludes the question-and-answer session. I'll turn the call back over to Mr. Glazer for any closing remarks.
Michael L. Glazer - President, Chief Executive Officer & Director
Great. Well, thanks everyone. A lot of good questions there and thank you for joining us today. We look forward to speaking with you again after the conclusion of our second quarter. Thank you very much, everyone.
Operator
This concludes today's conference call. You may now disconnect.
